Biker reacts lighting-fast and prevents the worst
On Friday evening, there was a traffic accident on the country road between Machtolsheim and Merklingen, where the motorcyclist only suffered minor injuries thanks to his quick reaction.
Car driver doesn’t see biker
A 44-year old car driver coming from Merklingen wanted to make a left turn onto country road 1230 towards Machtolsheim around 9:30 p.m. in her VW.
She did not see the 24-year old motorcyclist coming from Nellingen who had the right of way.
During the collision, the hand brake and foot brake lever flew off
The biker tried to evade the car, but still hit the rear of the vehicle.
Grazing the car caused the Suzuki’s hand and foot brake levers to be torn off and the driver was no longer able to brake.
Alert, he steered his motorcycle into the median strip next to the roadway and let the motorcycle coast to a stop there.
Biker suffers leg injury
The biker did suffer a leg injury from the impact with the car and had to be treated at a hospital.
Mamming: Coronavirus mass infections: 174 farmhands infected
Following a coronavirus mass infection in a large vegetable farm in Mamming in lower Bavaria, nearly 500 people are under quarantine and not allowed to leave the farm.
A security service is monitoring the confinement.
A total of 174 farmhands tested positive for the coronavirus pathogen Sars-CoV-2 during mass testing, as the district office of Dingolfing-Landau announced on Saturday evening.
“To prevent further spread, we unfortunately need to take this step to protect the population,” stated district administrator Werner Bumeder (CSU).
Seven employees were previously infected on the farm - this was the reason for the mass testing.
The business is a large vegetable farm, which cultivates raspberries, cucumbers, cabbages and beets - but the cucumbers are only for pickling jars.
Mamming is a rural community with approximately 3,300 residents, not far from Dingolfing’s large BMW plant.
Bumeder appealed to the citizens to stay calm: “According to our information, this is a closed group of people.”
On the farm, infected employees were kept separated from non-infected employees, and the premises are now surrounded by a fence.
The Green and SPD parties blamed the state government.
The two opposing factions accused Minister-President Markus Söder (CSU) and his cabinet of failing to control the seasonal workers’ accommodation.
“This could pay dearly if local infections like this spread and regional lockdowns have to be arranged,” said Jürgen Mistol, the parliamentary director of the Green Party.
The SPD sees it very similarly: “After the coronavirus outbreak in the Wiesenhof butchery in mid-May, we called for a special control program, including for farms with seasonal workers,” said environmental expert Florian von Brunn.
“The hygiene conditions in the workplace and the living conditions need to be heavily controlled, in our opinion.
Obviously this didn’t happen.”
The outbreak happened “on cue.”
Aidenbachstrasse underground station: Dangerous brawl: 19-year old falls to track bed after being pushed
During an argument between two groups of youths at the Aidenbachstrasse underground station, a 19-year old was pushed to the ground and slipped into the track bed.
Obersendling - At around 4:15 p.m. on Friday, there was a quarrel between two groups of youths at Aidenbachstrasse underground station.
A passer-by alerted the police, and a number of officers attended the scene.
Initial inquiries indicate that a youth (17) from Munich pushed a 19-year old man to the floor.
The young man then slipped over the edge of the platform and fell into the track bed.
Members of the 17-year old’s group helped the man who had fallen to climb back on to the platform.
There was no danger from an oncoming train.
As reported by the police, the two young people then resumed their dispute.
The 17-year old initially fled from the scene, but his identity was later verified.
His father accompanied him to police station number 29.
The 17-year old is under investigation for causing bodily harm.
Report: Seehofer pushes for longer data retention
Data retention is currently suspended.
But according to a media report, the Federal Minister of the Interior, Horst Seehofer, is calling for an extension of the retention period.
His aim is to strengthen the fight against child abuse.
According to a media report, Federal Minister of the Interior Horst Seehofer (CSU) is calling for data retention to be extended - for six months rather than ten weeks.
As “Bild am Sonntag” reports, Seehofer asked Justice Minister Christine Lambrecht (SPD) for a quick change to the law in a letter.
It reports that Seehofer’s intention is to strengthen measures against child abuse.
He believes it is a good idea “to make urgently required changes to the law now”, the paper quotes the letter.
Data retention is currently suspended.
An ECJ decision on it is still outstanding.
However, Seehofer wants the changes beforehand so that they can be applied immediately if the verdict is positive, the report goes on to say.
A Justice Ministry spokesman told the paper that they could only really look to see whether legal change is necessary once the courts have reached a decision.
In the fight against child abuse and child pornography, Seehofer and the federal states’ interior ministers had previously argued in favor of data retention back in June.
NBA: Strip club problem for Clippers star Lou Williams
Trouble in the NBA!
Lou Williams (33), basketball pro with the Los Angeles Clippers, had supposedly left the tournament accommodation in Disney World in Orlando/Florida with permission to attend a funeral.
But according to US media reports, he visited the “Magic City” strip club in Atlanta that evening.
Williams, who, according to ESPN, has apparently admitted to the visit, is back in isolation and being tested every day for Covid-19.
The reason for his visit? Chicken wings.
Back in February last year, “Sweet Lou”, as he is known in the NBA, expressed his liking for those same wings.
The American wrote, "Magic City and Blue Flame (another strip club in Atlanta, Ed. ) have the best wings in the city”.
On Sunday NBA insider Shams Charania announced on Twitter that the NBA had ordered Williams to go into quarantine for ten days.
This means that the Clippers star will miss the first two official games after the test game phase.
The NBA is aiming to play out the coronavirus season in Disney World.
The best 22 teams are currently playing training games in preparation for the season finale which begins on Friday night.
Söder makes a statement about coronavirus situation after mass infections
Munich - Health Minister Melanie Huml (CSU) already announced a testing offensive for large farms on Sunday.
The press conference can be viewed live on our homepage.
The case in Mamming in the district of Dingolfing-Landau has frightened authorities and politicians.
There are currently almost 500 harvesting workers from several countries working on the large vegetable farm, and over one third of them are infected with the coronavirus pathogen.
The farm is now under quarantine and is blocked off with fencing.
No one is allowed to leave the premises, food is being delivered.
The authorities are now offering free coronavirus tests to the almost 3,300 residents of the municipality.
Since the farmhands had little contact with the local population, the district office is currently assuming that the infections have not spread beyond the farm.
“Pangs of conscience”: Confession of the alleged Nantes arsonist
“My client has cooperated,” lawyer Quentin Chabert told the newspaper.
The defense counsel added, “He very much regrets his actions, and his confession came as a relief to him”.
His client was “plagued by pangs of conscience and upset by the extent of the damage”.
The prosecution service say that, if he is convicted, the man faces ten years in prison and a 150,000 euro fine.
Last Saturday night, the Gothic St Peter and St Paul Cathedral in Nantes was severely damaged by a fire.
The fire broke out at three separate locations in the church.
Laboratory investigations firmed up the suspicion of arson.
The suspect now in custody was detained just hours after the fire.
But after a day he was released.
The man works for the Nantes diocese in a voluntary capacity and he was responsible for locking up the cathedral on the evening before the fire.
As there was no evidence of forced entry into the church, he quickly came under the scrutiny of the investigators.
Discussion about scrapping the 50+1 rule
Former DFB President Reinhard Grindel has recommended thought be given to scrapping the 50+1 rule.
“German football should at least discuss setting conditions and clear rules for investors before the EU Commission creates any fait accompli,” Grindel told “Bild am Sonntag”.
He said, “In any case the 50+1 rules don’t work for those clubs that are most likely to threaten Bayern and Dortmund - look at Leipzig or Leverkusen.
In any case, you can’t get around the debate as to whether it shouldn’t be made easier for clubs that are aiming to break into this grouping to engage investors.
But he doubts whether there is a willingness within the German football league to allow majority shareholdings which are prohibited by the 50+1 rule in the Bundesliga.
“There is a legal risk involved in putting up investment barriers around the Bundesliga as a business hub in a European internal market,” said Grindel.
The former DFB boss sees a danger that “the attempts to create a greater competitive balance in the Bundesliga could, in the end, merely weaken the competitiveness of our top clubs at European level, but not lead to more suspense in the championship”.
Even evenly distributing TV monies will not have any decisive effect.
“FC Bayern have revenues of 750 million euros, Borussia Dortmund 500 million and RB Leipzig 300 million.
So even between the top three clubs there are immense differences.
The other 15 clubs have an average budget of 130 million,” explained the 58 year old.
Looking back, Grindel feels betrayed.
“Unfortunately, there were individuals who noticed that error and went to the press rather than speak to me about it,” said Grindel about his acceptance of an expensive watch, which led to his resignation in April 2019.
“On a human level, that hurt me a lot”.
He had received the gift, valued at around 11,000 euros, from a Ukrainian functionary.
“I committed a compliance violation and it was right to accept the consequences,” said Grindel.
“I was completely transparent and honest about the dubious gift of the watch.
Many people at the DFB knew about it”.
He had never “made any secret of the gift”, affirmed the 58 year old.
“You might call that naive, but this type of transparency was the complete opposite of corruption”.
"Black Lives Matter": Casualties and one dead
In the United States there has been an upsurge in protests against police violence as a result of Donald Trump’s deployment of federal police in several cities.
There were clashes between demonstrators and police in various cities on Saturday.
Three people were injured in Louisville, while 16 people were detained in Seattle.
In Austin, one person was fatally shot as a demonstration was crossing a junction.
There had also been clashes during protests against racism and police violence in Portland previously.
On Saturday night the security forces, including federal police agents, deployed tear gas and dispersed demonstrators with force.
On Saturday hundreds of demonstrators, some armed, marched through Louisville in Kentucky and demanded that those responsible for the death of Breonna Taylor be held to account.
In March, the 26 year old student was shot in her apartment in Louisville during a drug raid.
The raid was targeting someone else who did not even live there, and no drugs were found.
On Saturday, when a member of a group calling itself the Armed Coalition of Black Americans fired a shot, three people were wounded.
According to broadcaster NBC, they were taken to hospital.
None of them was in a life-threatening condition.
The police formed barricades because counter-demonstrators from a white militia had also gathered.
In the end, the two groups did not clash.
In Austin, Texas, a person in a “Black Lives Matter” march was shot and killed.
According to some reports, the police have taken a suspect into custody.
They have not yet provided any further details about the circumstances surrounding the incident.
According to the New York Times, Mayor Steve Adler stated that, like many people in the city, he was “heartbroken and stunned” by what had happened.
On Saturday, demonstrators also clashed with police in the American city of Seattle.
They set fire to construction trailers in front of a youth detention center, and the police deployed flashbangs and pepper spray.
The “Seattle Times” reported that 16 people were detained for resisting police or for bodily harm.
A court building was set on fire in the city of Oakland in California.
A small group of demonstrators smashed windows, set off fireworks and blinded police officers with lasers, the Oakland police reported late on Saturday evening (local time).
The fire was quickly extinguished.
In Aurora, a suburb of Denver in Colorado, a car drove through a crowd of people who were demonstrating on a freeway.
As the police reported, one of the demonstrators fired a weapon, and at least one person was injured and taken to hospital.
There, too, windows in a court building were smashed and a fire was started, police reported.
An investigation has begun.
Rakoczi in Bad Kissingen: Historic costumes despite virus
Even though the spa town lacked the big party atmosphere, both visitors and performers enjoyed the flair of the alternative Rakoczi program.
It was unusual for visitors, performers and organisers alike. The Rakoczi weekend with no Rakoczi party.
However, even if the big party was absent from the town center, many people still got to enjoy the alternative, Covid-compliant program, including the crowds of people and highlights such as the Saale burning, the Rakoczi ball and the parade.
“I think we succeeded in creating plenty of Rakoczi flair,” said Spa Manager Sylvie Thormann.
It went down well with the guests.
In principle, it was a return to the beginnings of the Rakoczi Festival, when everything focused on the historic aspects.
Pleasant atmosphere
Vesna Konhäuser has been attending the Rakoczi Festival in Bad Kissingen with her husband for over 25 years.
She did so in this Covid year, too.
The couple settled down at the Luitpold Casino, watched the historic characters promenade, and listened to live Cuban music from the casino’s restaurant.
“I’m think it’s still really pleasant like this,” said Konhäuser.
She wasn’t missing the crowds of people which are usually associated with the Rakoczi.
However, she was missing the usual program highlights, particularly the burning Saale on Friday evening, the historic parad,e and the closing firework display on Sunday evening.
“It’s certainly a shame.
The weather was absolutely spot-on this year,” she felt.
Rakoczi horse show to be held again
For some of those portraying the historic spa guests, the alternative program meant more work.
For example, for Christina Gold who, in a normal year, takes part in the parade where she can be seen on the spa garden cafe’s carriage.
This year she spent Saturday and Sunday walking around town in her costume.
“It’s certainly more effort, we usually have things easier,” she said.
The riding club had less to do, even though a few riders were trotting around the park.
“We really hope that the riders’ quadrille will be held again next year,” said President Ulrike Waldhofen.
She said that a Rakoczi horse show would also be held again in 2021 after a hiatus of several years.
28 coronavirus cases at Spanish second division club Fuenlabrada
Spanish second division football club Fuenlabrada is slipping ever deeper into a crisis due to a coronavirus outbreak.
One blow has followed another since the newcomer from near Madrid flew to a game in the city of A Coruña on 20th July despite some cases of coronavirus.
By Sunday 28 players or team members had tested positive, with one hospitalized, the club reported.
Until now Fuenlabrada, from the eponymous town south-west of Madrid, had had a chance of reaching the promotion playoffs.
Now they are even threatened with relegation to the second division’s B Group.
The match against Deportivo La Coruña last Monday was canceled at the last moment, the public prosecutor was investigating a possible offence against public health, and the leading sports authority, the CSD, was considering imposing relegation on the club.
The players and other team members are in quarantine in a hotel.
“They were given no fresh towels and no shower gel until their sixth day of quarantine,” wrote sports paper “AS”.
Photos show that players have hung up underwear and club clothing in their hotel rooms after apparently having had to wash them themselves.
Neither had the bedding been washed for five days.
Food is another problem.
It is neither good nor enough,” wrote “AS”.
The club’s management stated that they are satisfied with the hotel.
The club’s lawyer, Javier Tebas Llanas, hit back at the accusation that they had committed an offence against public health.
Javier Tebas, who is the son of the President of Spain’s Primera Liga, said that they had not contravened the football association’s coronavirus regulations, reported news agency Europa Press and sports paper “Marca”.
Before flying, four people had been infected prior to 19th July, and they had all isolated and did not travel.
All the players and team members were retested immediately before the flight to A Coruña.
Once the team was in A Coruña “five or six” more team members then tested positive for coronavirus.
The game was cancelled 60 minutes before kick-off, said Tebas Llanas.
Police forced to catch runaway horses near Dampfach
Two animals had got onto the road.
The police led them back to their owner.
Shortly before 6 am on Sunday morning, a road user reported that there were two runaway horses on the slip road between the Donnersdorf/Steinsfeld junction and the Theres motorway access.
When the officers arrived, the horses were between the slip road and the village of Dampfach once more.
Once the officers had gained the horses’ trust near Dampfach, they allowed a rope that had been brought in the patrol car to be placed around them.
Cyclist Tony Martin: May extend career
Time trial specialist Tony Martin is considering extending his career.
Frankfurt/Main - Seven time world champion time trialist Tony Martin can certainly see himself continuing his cycling career.
“At the moment I’m talking with the team to work out exactly how we can continue,” the 35-year old told the "Frankfurter Allgemeine Sonntagszeitung".
Martin is currently employed by Dutch team Jumbo-Visma and, prior to the coronavirus break, he had been thinking about ending his career after this year.
The negotiations with his team include discussing the number of race days, he said.
Plus other issues that would affect him as a father, he added.
After falling, he used to get up and his first thought was, “Get back on the bike quickly!
Now, as th father of a little girl, I think: what if?”.
Martin admitted that there are issues that he finds increasingly difficult.
“But it did me good, during the virus, to see what I’ve got from cycling and how much I enjoy it”.
The time trial specialist’s next race will be the Tour de l'Ain (5th to 9th August).
Bavaria: At least four dead on Bavaria’s roads at the weekend
The fine weather drew bikers onto the roads in many places.
For at least three people, their bike ride ended in death.
An 18 year old pedestrian was also killed.
Schönthal - Several people, mostly young, died on Bavaria’s roads at the weekend.
Near Schönthal (Cham rural district) on Sunday, an 18 year old woman riding a motorbike was hit by an oncoming car that crossed into her lane.
Why the vehicle strayed into her lane was initially unclear.
In Upper Bavaria on Saturday, a 22 year old on a bike collided with a horse-drawn carriage.
According to police, he was riding downhill near Beilngries.
He collided with the carriage on a left-hand bend.
His injuries were so severe that he died at the scene.
Of the twelve occupants in the carriage, one man was seriously injured and one man sustained mild injuries, said the police.
An 18 year old died in another fatal accident in Bad Kötzting, in Upper Palatinate.
Late on Saturday night, he had lain down on a road and he was run over by a 42 year old driver.
The police believe that the 18 year old was trying to sleep.
The driver was unable to brake in time.
On Saturday near Schönberg (Freyung-Grafenau rural district), a 57-year-old biker hit a car head-on on a right-hand bend despite braking hard.
He died at the scene.
The 57 year old female driver suffered shock, while the other three people in the car were unhurt.
Bavaria’s Transport Minister Kerstin Schreyer (CSU) touched on the subject of motorcyclist safety on Saturday.
In a letter to Gabor Kovacs, the organizer of the biker protests against driving bans which are planned for August, the Minister referred to substantial investments such as underride guards on crash barriers, and the straightening of dangerous bends.
“We have done a lot for motorcyclist safety in recent years,” said the letter.
“The number of motorcyclist fatalities has fallen by around 28 percent compared with 2011”.
Kovac tested as Monaco play Frankfurt
Frankfurt/Main (dpa) - Football coach Niko Kovac is soon to play against Eintracht Frankfurt again with his new club AS Monaco.
The eight-time French champions are set to visit the Hesse outfit, the Croat’s previous club, on August 1st (6 p.m.).
For the Bundesliga outfit, this is their one and only endurance test prior to their Europa League return against FC Basel (6th August).
The match will go ahead without spectators due to the coronavirus pandemic.
“We’re particularly looking forward to this game.
It’s always nice to come to Frankfurt and meet up with friends,” explained Kovac.
In sporting terms it would be a good test, said the 48 year old.
Before switching to Bayern Munich, Kovac coached the Hesse club between 2016 and 2018 and led them to victory in the DFB Cup.
“A quality opponent like Monaco is a good test for us with respect to the game against Basel.
Like everyone at Frankfurt, I’m looking forward to seeing Niko Kovac again,” said Eintracht coach Adi Hütter.
The 50 year old Austrian took over from the Croat at Eintracht.
In March, Frankfurt lost the first leg of the quarter finals against Basel 0:3 in their own stadium.
Nearly 50 new infections: The district of Hof has nearly finished lockdown
The number of known new coronavirus infections in the district of Hof increased again on the weekend: from 39 on Friday and 43 on Saturday (one person has recovered and is no longer included in this statistic) to 47 on Sunday.
There is also one case in the city of Hof.
This means that the area of Hof is reaching the critical mark of 50 new infections per 100,000 residents in a week.
700 killed by monsoon rains in South-East Asia
Over 9 million people have been affected by the severe flooding in South-East Asia, particularly in Bangladesh, India and Nepal.
In all, 700 people have died as a result of the strong monsoon rains.
In Bangladesh, the Red Crescent are attempting to reach isolated people in boats.
Entire villages are under water.
The farmers have lost their harvests.
Indian rhinos die after landslide in national park
Several of the 120 Indian rhinos in the Kaziranga National Park died as a result of a landslide.
They are protected and considered to be under threat of extinction.
This year the flooding is particularly bad, which scientists are attributing to climate change.
According to United Nations data, Bangladesh is one of the countries most affected by global warming.
New apartments stand empty
In the city of Cox’s Bazar in southern Bangladesh, the state has built apartments for 650 people who have been driven out by the floods.
Only a few have so far been occupied.
It is difficult to get people to Cox’s Bazar.
There is limited enthusiasm, too.
Those who used to own a house, albeit small and hut-like, often do not want to spend their lives in a large apartment building.
Many of the apartments are vacant, but the government wants them to soon be occupied by those who have lost their house to the floods.
60 New Coronavirus Infections in one day in Vienna
