Argentina rejects creditors’ counter-offer
The new claim could not be settled, the Finance Ministry in Buenos Aires stated on Saturday.
“It would be not just irresponsible, but unjust too,” a statement explained.
“While 50 percent of children in Argentina are living in poverty, we cannot increase our creditors’ short-term profits”.
The debts of the second-largest national economy in South America are no longer sustainable under the current terms.
As a result, Argentina is asking its private creditors to waive some of their claims of around 66 billion US Dollars (about 59 billion euros).
Should no agreement be reached, the country will once again be threatened with bankruptcy.
That would be the ninth debt default in Argentina’s history.
Creditors have recently demanded higher interest rates on government securities, and changes to some contractual clauses.
However, the Argentinian government is sticking to its last offer and is not prepared to make any further concessions.
Argentina is in the middle of a severe financial and economic crisis.
The inflation rate was recently above 50 percent.
Experts are expecting a decline in economic output of around ten percent this year.
In late May, Argentina failed to make interest payments of 503 million US Dollars, so it slipped into partial debt default.
Arrived professionally - not yet personally
“It’s going really well” Dr. Stefanie Kramer drew this conclusion after her first days in the notary’s office in Eggenfelden.
In the end, everything happened very quickly: In Mid-May, Dr. Stefanie Kramer learned that she was taking Lutz Feller’s old position in the Eggenfelden notary’s office.
Six weeks later, in early July, the doctor of law began work, and normal daily business has been at full speed for a while.
“However, I still have to arrive personally,” she says in a conversation with the Rottaler Anzeiger and laughs.
Of course the short lead time was not enough to time to completely move the center of her life from Regensburg to Eggenfelden, reports the Dingolfing native.
She is currently searching for a suitable apartment or house in the city with her husband, who works in Regensburg as a judge on the district court.
At least her husband was able to apply for short-term parental leave to be able to ensure their two daughters (3½ and 1½ years old) are cared for.
So as not to have to commute from Regensburg every day, she can stay with her parents in Dingolfing for now, says the 39 year old.
Having grown up in the neighboring district, she is of course very familiar with the city of Eggenfelden.
When visiting on site with her family in recent months, she once again noticed: “Eggenfelden is a really nice little city.”
So she was all the more happy when she found out she had won the race for the position in the selection procedure.
Even in Dr. Stefanie Kramer’s professional career, her home of Lower Bavaria plays a key role: After studying law in Passau, she completed her legal clerkship and 2nd state examination in Regensburg.
After several stops as a notary public, including in Rehau and Hof in Upper Franconia, Babenhausen in Unterallgäu and Regensburg - during this time she also shouldered her doctorate in labor law “on the side” - she started her first position as a notary in Rotthalmünster in the district of Passau in 2012.
In 2016, she went on parental leave, this was finally followed by the move to Regensburg.
Since then she has been doing representative services in various notary offices.
When the position in Eggenfelden opened up due to the approaching retirement of Lutz Feller, she saw it as the right time to make the full re-entry into her career, says the 39-year old.
Dr. Stefanie Kramer has completely taken over the predecessor’s team, who will in the future take over the notary’s office for vacation representation - and already has praise for the office’s team: “It’s going really well!”
The fact that she can rely on the smooth-running processes makes it easier for her to take care of the upcoming relocation of her private life.
In terms of kindergarten or daycare places, she has already contacted the local facilities.
And if everything goes as she hopes, she will be able to pursue her hobby here as well - and get to know the best jogging routes in the Rottal.
BVB plans for up to 15,000 fans when new season opens
Dortmund Germany’s largest football stadium, in Dortmund, will not even be 20 percent full at the start of next season should fans return.
“Because of the rules on distancing we have to comply with, we are currently planning for between 12,000 and 15,000 fans”, Borussia Dortmund director Carsten Cramer told "Tagesspiegel".
The Dortmund arena normally holds a little over 81,000 spectators for Bundesliga games.
Last season BVB lost around four million euros per match as games were played behind closed doors due to the coronavirus pandemic.
Cramer, who is Head of Marketing, Digitalization and Internationalization at BVB, is hoping that they will be able to open up some of the approximately 4,000 seats in the hospitality area, as well as the normal seats. “Of course, it’s a financial blow if all of this revenue is lost.”
Given the ongoing Covid-19 crisis, everyone would be “well advised to adopt a recovery position to begin with”.
“If a lot companies are having difficulties and 6.8 million people are working reduced hours in Germany alone, the need for entertainment is limited,” explained Cramer.
The Dortmund marketing boss praised the BVB players for giving up part of their salary in order to help get through the crisis, “Of course, the players know that giving up their salaries has a different effect than if we reduce the working hours of 100 people in merchandising.”
Tiny miracles: Early life start at only a couple hundred grams
Scarcely heavier than a packet of butter, just three tablespoons of blood in his entire body. That was Gabriel when he was born - he weighed precisely 273 grams.
The tot is one of around 400 premature babies that the Graz Children’s Hospital cares for each year.
A quarter of them weigh less than 1,500 grams, while a couple, such as Gabriel and his brothers Raphael and Michael, are extreme lightweights whose birth weight is not even a kilogram.
They are so small and born so early that their lungs, intestines and muscles are not fully formed.
Their skin is sometimes so tender that an ECG’s electrodes can damage it.
And they are so tiny that, for a while, they wear dolls’ clothing and diapers specially made for them.
But not so small that they have no voice - “And how!”, smiles Berndt Urlesberger.
“Even though they don’t cry as loudly as large babies, of course”.
When the whiteboard becomes the stage
Theater in the classroom despite the coronavirus: The 9th grade class of the St. Jakobus High School in Abtsgmünd found out just before the start of the holidays that the white board can be experienced as a stage.
Actress Julia Sylvester from the city theater in Aalen put on the production “Das Heimatkleid” for students - by video, in fact.
The students were then able to talk with the actress and director Winfried Tobias about the piece and the performance afterwards via Skype.
The idea for the performance format was borne out of the current coronavirus situation.
Teacher Teresa Nar was pleased with the enrichment to her teaching.
Even though all of the participants agreed at the end that the direct encounter in the theater, and on stage, would be more appealing, potential for contact in schools can also be seen in the theater.
“If we continue to improve the technical framework, it could be an interesting supplement to productions,” emphasized director Winfried Tobias.
First Round draw: TSV 1860 to meet Eintracht Frankfurt in the DFB Cup
If TSV 1860 qualify for the DFB Cup, the Lions will face Eintracht Frankfurt in the first round.
This was the outcome of Sunday’s draw.
Munich 1860’s potential opponent in the first round of the DFB Cup is now known.
If the Lions qualify they will face Eintracht Frankfurt.
This was the outcome of the draw in the ARD sports show on Sunday evening.
As the participants have not yet been finalized due to the coronavirus pandemic, the draw made use of placeholders.
As semi-final opponents FC Memmingen have voluntarily withdrawn, TSV 1860 are already in the final of the Bavarian Cup (4th or 5th September).
There the Lions will face either the Würzburger Kickers or Viktoria Aschaffenburg.
If Würzburg, who were recently promoted to Division 2 of the Bundesliga, reach the final, 1860 would already qualify for the first round of the DFB Cup.
