Heil intends looking at other sectors after the meat industry.
The coronavirus crisis has again exposed conditions in parts of the meat industry.
Tightened laws on the way
But are they legal - and will they stick?
Following on from the tough rules that are now planned against failings in the meat industry, the Federal Minister of Employment, Hubertus Heil (SPD), is also intending to look at other sectors.
“We shall study them sector by sector and then, if required, take suitable measures for the sector concerned,” Heil told the Deutsche Presse agency in Berlin.
German employers are already warning against generally restricting work contracts.
After the massive coronavirus outbreak at meat giant Tönnies in North Rhine-Westphalia, the federal cabinet is intending to enact one of Heil’s laws this Wednesday.
Large slaughterhouses will no longer be permitted to employ third party staff for slaughtering, cutting or meat processing.
And the use of work contracts and temporary staff is also set to be banned.
Employers’ President Ingo Kramer told the dpa, “Stay away from any general restriction on work contracts and contract staffing if you don’t want to completely choke the economy”.
For example, for broad sections of the skilled crafts sector, the construction industry and plant engineering, work contracts are the very basis of their added value for the customer.
“Individual failings cannot ruin a key instrument like this.”
Heil promised, “My aim isn’t to ban work contracts everywhere in German business.”
Work contracts make good sense.
“When an industrial company hires a skilled person to install a safety system, that’s a completely normal work contract”.
The German meat industry believes that banning work contracts and temporary employment in their sector alone is unconstitutional.
There was no explanation as to why, in the future, the employment law applied to cutting up and packaging cheese should be different to that applied to sausage, said a statement on the planned legislation, as the "Neue Osnabrücker Zeitung" reported (Saturday).
Were there to be a ban, the consumer price would rise by 10 to 20 percent per kilo.
Many Eastern European workers in contractor companies in the sector were sometimes working 16 hours per day, according to the findings of an investigation by NRW’s Employment Protection Office.
They often had no breaks.
Wages were held back for protective equipment or rent.
It was also found that workers’ accommodation situations were often poor.
Heil said that a relatively tough law for the meat industry had been passed in 2017.
But they had been circumvented by “cunning systems”.
“Now a complete deep-clean is required”.
The politician said, “The employment protection law that we in the cabinet want to pass in late July also contains measures that affect not only the meat sector - for example, higher check rates for employment protection and clear criteria for shared accommodation”.
The draft available to the dpa contains amendments to the law on safeguarding employee rights in the meat industry and the employment protection law.
Brandenburg’s Consumer Protection Minister Ursula Nonnemacher (Greens) believes tighter controls are necessary.
“I’d like to be able to carry out even more inspections in many supervisory areas: food inspections, animal protection, everything possible, for example animal transport too,” Nonnemacher said in the RBB program "Brandenburg aktuell" on Sunday.
But more staff would also be required for any increase in inspections.
