The foundation has long complained that visitors always leave behind trash and would destroy protected biotopes.
In Berlin, illegal park parties have reached a new dimension.
In the Hasenheide park in the district of Neukölln, 5,000 people had an illegal techno party Saturday night.
The police broke up the party.
Austria: Mass testing after coronavirus outbreak in tourist resort
Authorities have responded to a coronavirus outbreak with hundreds of tests in the popular Upper Austrian tourist resort of St. Wolfgang.
The number of confirmed cases rose to 48, according to regional authorities in Linz.
By the evening, over 100 results were still outstanding.
They report that many of those infected are young interns in tourist businesses, though at least one holidaymaker had also tested positive.
Residents, guests and tourism personnel were asked to remain in their accommodation on Saturday evening.
An 11 p.m. curfew was set.
“There have been cancellations here and there,” the Head of the Wolfgangsee Tourism Association, Hans Wieser, told the dpa.
A few guests had also departed early.
St. Wolfgang is the biggest tourist resort in Upper Austria, with over 400,000 overnight stays last year.
In a normal season, around one third of visitors are German.
The first infections were announced on Friday.
On Saturday the head of the district authority, Alois Lanz, defended the behavior of the interns, who had been partying in various bars and could have become infected there.
“We all enjoyed doing that when we were young,” he told the Ö1 radio station.
However, two bars were closed on Friday to prevent further infections.
The Tourism Association initiated an information campaign to raise young employees’ awareness of the dangers of Covid-19.
Then, from Saturday, hundreds of staff, holidaymakers and locals were tested.
All visitors who had been to St. Wolfgang since 15th July were also contacted.
The outbreak is a reminder of the Austrian ski and party resort Ischgl in Tirol, which was a center for the spread of the virus throughout Europe in the initial phase of the pandemic.
Over 1500 people, in all, are currently infected with the virus in Austria.
Vienna and Upper Austria have particularly high levels of new infections.
Premier League: Man United and Chelsea qualify for Champions League
London (dpa)- The English soccer record champion Manchester United returns to the Champions League after a year being absent.
The Red Devils secured the third ranking on the last day of play in the Premier League with a 2:0 (0:0) win against direct competitors Leicester City.
The Foxes now have to content themselves with the Europa League, because FC Chelsea passed them and qualified in fourth place for the Champions League.
Aston Villa can celebrate in the fight against relegation.
Manchester United took the lead thanks to a penalty kick by Bruno Fernandes (71st minute).
After a red card for Leicester City during injury time, Jesse Lingard (90th + 8) scored the final goal.
Chelsea, opponent to FC Bayern in the Champions League quarter finals, won in parallel thanks to Mason Mount (45th minute + 1) and Olivier Giroud (45th minute + 4) with 2:0 (2:0) against the Wolverhampton Wanderers.
“This means a lot to me,” said trainer Frank Lampard, who is also in the final of the FA Cup against Arsenal in his first season as the Chelsea coach.
Tottenham Hotspurs also benefitted from Chelsea’s victory against Wolverhampton, moving past Wolves with a meager 1:1 (1:0) victory at Crystal Palace and starting in sixth place in the Europa League.
Aston Villa won the standing battle with FC Watford and AFC Bournemouth, but were nervous about staying in the league when playing West Ham United.
The late lead by Jack Grealish (84th minute) was immediately equalized by Andrej Jarmolenko (85th minute).
The 1:1 (0:0) sufficed though, because Watford lost at Arsenal 2:3 (1:3).
The club, which sacked three coaches this season, is being relegated after five years in the top league.
Just like Bournemouth, which couldn’t save itself with a 3:1 (2:1) win at FC Everton.
They were missing a point in the end.
FC Liverpool, which has already been crowned the English champion since the end of June, set a club record with a 3:1 (1:1) win at Newcastle United.
99 points is the most that the Reds have ever achieved in a single soccer season.
Coach Jürgen Klopp and his team just narrowly missed the point record in English soccer.
The record is held by Manchester City with 100 points in the 2017/2018 season.
After the Newcastle lead in the first minute, Virgil van Dijk (38th), Divock Origi (59th) and Sadio Mané (89th minute) turned the tide for Liverpool on Sunday.
“It was an exceptional season for this wonderful club,” said goal scorer van Dijk after the game, “this should spur us on to defend the title.
It will be tough.”
The Premier League bosses may also be happy in the end.
Due to the coronavirus crisis, soccer in England was halted from March 13 to June 17.
In between, there was even talk of ending the season early or playing the rest of the games on neutral territory.
Ultimately, however, the season was played out to the end without incident - although, like in Germany, without spectators in the stadiums.
Arrests and violence at demonstrations against Netanyahu
Protests in Israel against the government head Netanyahu are becoming more intense.
There were violent clashes overnight.
The Israeli police took violent action against participants of a demonstration against the right-wing conservative head of government Benjamin Netanyahu Saturday night in Jerusalem.
Two people were arrested for their participation in the unrest, according to police spokesman Micky Rosenfeld.
The police used water cannons, among other things, to break up the demonstration.
According to media reports, around 6,000 people in total gathered near Netanyahu’s official residence on Saturday night.
They were protesting against unemployment, corruption and Netanyahu’s handling of the coronavirus crisis.
The protestors beat drums, blew horns and called for Netanyahu to resign.
Participants of a counter-demonstration who supported Netanyahu were also arrested, reports the news site “ynet.”
People also demonstrated in many other places in Israel, including in front of the private villa of the head of government in the coastal city of Caesarea and in a park in Tel Aviv.
According to police information, a man was arrested near Tel Aviv, because he was suspected of spraying pepper spray on demonstrators on the edge of the street out of a driving car.
Another man was arrested after a knife attack on a demonstrator in the south of the country.
The demonstrator suffered a minor neck injury.
There have been multiple demonstrations against Netanyahu in Jerusalem and Tel Aviv recently.
The demonstrations are accompanying the corruption trial against the head of the government.
Netanyahu has also been recently criticized for his handling of the coronavirus crisis.
Among other complaints, he has been criticized of loosening restrictions too soon and not being well-prepared for a second wave of the coronavirus.
The coronavirus crisis has severely impaired the country’s economy.
The unemployment rate was most recently at more than 20 percent.
The number of new infections of coronavirus in Israel has recently risen to new records.
Accident near Ahlen (North Rhine Westphalia) - Van crashes into car - nine injured - Ruhr - Bild.de
Ahlen - A rear-end collision left nine people with minor injuries on Saturday afternoon on the B58 near Ahlen.
A woman was driving towards Beckum with her two children (3 and 5).
According to police, “She probably braked suddenly because she wanted to turn off”.
The driver of a Mercedes van who was behind her spotted it too late.
