Several ambulances took them to a nearby hospital.
North Korea closes off border city after suspected coronavirus case
North Korea views its own measures to protect against the coronavirus as a “gleaming success.”
Now the country is reporting a suspected case for the first time.
Due to a first official suspected case of coronavirus in the country, North Korea has completely shut down a major city out of fear of a disaster.
Despite the strictest epidemiological defensive measures in the past six months, “the virulent virus was still able to make its way into the country,” reports the state media.
A state of emergency has been called for the region around the border city of Kaesong.
The communistic government rang the highest alarm level.
If the suspected case is confirmed, it would be the first official case of infection with Sars-CoV-2 in the isolated country.
According to its own statements, North Korea has so far not registered any infections, and has described its defensive measures as a “gleaming success.”
The statements have been doubted abroad.
According to the reports, symptoms of the illness were found in a “runner” who illegally crossed the military demarcation line between South and North Korea on July 19.
The person defected to South Korea three years ago and has now returned over the border.
South Korea initially has given no confirmation of the border crossing within the military buffer zone that is four kilometers wide and is still mostly covered with land mines.
According to reports from the national news agency Yonhap, South Korea’s military considers the possibility of an illegal border crossing into North Korea as high.
There are ongoing investigations of several people.
According to its own statements, North Korea called an urgent meeting of the workers’ party politburo, chaired by leader Kim Jong Un, regarding the suspected case on Saturday.
The “dangerous situation in Kaesong could trigger a deadly and destructive disaster.”
Kim already arranged “to completely block off Kaesong and isolate every district and the region from each other as a preventative measure,” it continues.
The affected person, as well as all people in Kaesong who may have had contact with this person, have been placed under quarantine.
According to this, the party’s central military commission is set to investigate the “runner case” and the behavior of the responsible military unit, as well as possibly imposing strict punishments.
According to estimates, approximately 300,000 people live in Kaesong.
Tension before council meeting: East of the city and noise protection are up for discussion before the big summer break
“In addition to environmental topics, the committee members will also vote on the development plan for the major project of the inner city east development,” states the middle section of the city’s press release for the next municipal council meeting on Tuesday, July 28, at 4:30 p.m. in the large hall of the Congress Centrum Pforzheim.
However, the betterment of the eastern side of the city remains a bitter discussion to the very end.
The majority being in favor is tight, most recently even being rejected in individual committees, depending on attendance.
An appeal from the economy (construction, real estate, trade and IT) not to let the project, which was developed from the citizens and then by the administration of the municipal council, fail after nearly ten years of preparation was criticized by project critic Reinhard Klein as “extra-parliamentary opposition,” “naive,” “speculation,” “denigration” and “deliberate false statements.”
“Everyone thinks they know better,” says Klein, who has been part of the municipal council for a year as the only representative from the citizens’ party ticket of Pforzheim.
In fact, he said this was his position after reading the contracts: “I know what I am talking about.”
Abandoning the project would be cheaper for the city - contrary to the city administration’s statements, the technical city hall could be renovated for EUR 8.5 million with grants, the existence of which Klein is convinced of.
The city will develop very differently than predicted in the town hall and by the advocates from the local economy.
Designing the city on our own and not by an investor: That’s his plan B. One day later, Klein presented an alternative concept to the FDP/FW/UB/LED faction, who also rejected the project.
It essentially also provides for the renovation of the technical city hall, keeping the Schloßberg open, renting out the former Thales for administrative space, and a smaller inner city redesign in an ideal case with local providers.
Environmental topics play a key role
In addition, environmental issues play a key role here.
That is why the municipal council will also vote on the noise abatement plan.
This includes various measures to protect the Profzheim population against harmful noise caused by road traffic, including many speed reductions.
In a press release, local Verkehrsclub Deutschland [local chapter of German traffic club] welcomes the widespread introduction of a 30 km/h speed limit. City policy makers are partly to blame that this must be introduced, because they neglected the urban bus traffic with thinned out routes, and were not committed to bicycle traffic so that it lead to a massive increase in car traffic and therefore the noise level, says the Verkehrsclub Deutschland.
The municipal council will also vote on the city’s participation in the energy and climate protection agency of Pforzheim/Enzkreis.
In addition, entry into the climate protection pact of the state of Baden-Württemberg, redefining parental contributions to city daycare centers, and the application to be included in the federal government’s Smart City funding are all on the agenda.
Citizens are welcome, but must take a coronavirus protective measures.
Tim Zimmermann is starting the new season with a big delay
With almost a half of a year delay, Tim Zimmermann is starting his debut season in ADAC GT Masters on July 31.
Before the supercar league can resume regular operations, the first test runs must be performed.
For Zimmermann, this was primarily about getting to know his Lamborghini Huracan GT3 better.
The coronavirus has long prevented Tim Zimmermann from being able to take his first drive in the new Lamborghini Huracan from Grasser Racing.
This has now been possible under special hygiene conditions.
The 23-year-old Langenargen native drove his first laps on the Lausitzring and was able to get comfortable on his debut in the GT3 car.
“There are a few things that are different than with the Porsche from last season,” says Zimmermann.
“You can corner differently with the ABS, for example.
But it was really a ton of fun.”
Zimmermann also had fun with Steijn Schothorst with whom he will share his orange sportscar in the GT Masters.
The Dutchman is already experienced in the GT sport, despite only being 25 years old, and was able to help his new team colleague with many things.
“I’m not a beginner at motor sports, but every new series also brings new challenges with it,” says Zimmermann.
“Steijn and I get along wonderfully and we’ve made tremendous progress on the Lausitzring from session to session.”
The GT Masters will also have its first race here, at the Lausitzring.
33 supercars will race through the Lausitz on July 31.
Zimmermann, who is one of 15 series newbies, knows the track though.
In 2015, he was a guest at the Motodrom.
“It worked quickly and I had to get used the track a little,” says Zimmermann, who raced for the Friedrichshafen racing team Graf Zeppelin.
“The Lausitzring has a lot of fast passages that you have to hit perfectly to be fast.”
We’ll find out in two weeks how fast Zimmermann actually is.
“The teams of course push their luck a bit on the tests,” he says.
“Ultimately, though, we are very satisfied and are looking forward to the first weekend on the Lausitzring.”
The race in Brandenburg will be the kick-off to a tightly-packed calendar.
There are seven races on the docket by early November.
Currently no spectators are allowed - but there will be one prominent guest.
In mid-August on the Nürburgring, ex-Formula 1 pilot Niko Hülkenberg will take the GT wheel.
British traffic minister caught with his pants down by quarantine decision
The decision of the British government to place Spanish vacationers under quarantine for two weeks after their return has caught the traffic minister of the country with his pants down according to press reports.
According to the reports, Grant Schapps is currently on vacation in Spain, while his colleagues at home decided the measure on Saturday.
Due to the coronavirus numbers in Spain rising again, the cabinet in London struck the country from the list of countries you can return from without going into quarantine.
The new regulation goes into effect today, which means Schapps needs to go into quarantine after his return.
In Austria, the government has also imposed quarantine measures for those returning from vacation.
But the regulation applies to those who are on vacation starting on the cut-off date, which is Saturday August 1, and it was not introduced overnight.
Incidentally, Austria has considered Spain as one of the “safe countries” to date, and does not require any quarantine upon returning to Austria.
“Countless ministers must have known in advance that it was possible that a quarantine would be imposed for people vacationing in Spain,” commented the Labor representative Diane Abbot.
“But apparently no one made the effort to tell Grant Schapps.”
Less than a month after the end of the coronavirus state of emergency in Spain and the expiration of the strict lockdown, the number of infections in the country is rising again.
Virologists are pinning the recent spread on night life above all.
Spain is one of the most popular vacation countries among Brits.
The British government is advising against traveling to the Spanish mainland unless necessary, excluding the Canary Islands and Balearic Islands, which are particularly popular among British tourists.
To date, more than 272,000 infections with the novel coronavirus and more than 28,000 deaths have been registered in Spain.
Russia: Navy Day: Putin announces hypersonic weapons for warships
On Navy Day in his country, Russian President Vladimir Putin has announced that warships will be equipped with the latest hypersonic weapons.
These weapons, a world first, would increase the Russian naval forces’ fighting options, said Putin in St. Petersburg on Sunday at the central navy parade.
Afterwards the Defence Ministry also notified the Interfax agency that the Zirkon hypersonic missiles built for the navy had been tested successfully.
The hypersonic weapons have a speed of around 343 meters per second, many times faster than the speed of sound.
They are regarded as weapons of the future.
Development of underwater torpedo continues
It is said that the Poseidon underwater torpedo, to which atomic warheads can be fitted, is still being developed.
The planned underwater drone is aimed at destroying coastal targets.
The President, who also rode in a military boat, said that in this year alone, 40 new ships would come into service for the largest country in the world’s various naval units.
Russia has a larger coastal area than any other country in the world.
The navy has reliably protected Russia for 300 years, said Putin on the day celebrated by sailors throughout the country.
Naval forces at many other Russian coastal locations also celebrated the day with parades.
In Syria, where Russia is fighting beside ruler Bashar al-Assad, the military demonstrated its strength with a weapons display in the Mediterranean port of Tartus.
Shells were also fired there.
In a video released by the Defense Ministry, not only warships, including a submarine, were visible, but also combat helicopters and jets.
Hurricane “Hanna” reaches Texas: Aid impeded by coronavirus
Washington - The first hurricane of the season over the Atlantic has made landfall in Texas.
Life-threatening flooding, strong winds and heavy rainfall are now threatening parts of the US state, announced the National Hurricane Center of the US climate authority NOAA Saturday night (local time).
Governor Greg Abbott declared a state of emergency for numerous counties.
The coronavirus pandemic raging in Texas made work difficult for aid workers, Abbott said, according to US media.
Evacuees told to be cautious
“Every hurricane is a tremendous challenge,” Abbott said according to the newspaper “Houston Chronicle.”
With regard to the hurricane in Texas, he added: “This challenge is complicated and is exacerbated when you consider that it is sweeping through an area that is the most heavily hit by Covid-19 in the state.”
According to Johns-Hopkins University, around 5,000 people have died in Texas alone as a result of the coronavirus pandemic.
Abbott called on people who had to leave their homes to be cautious.
They should observe practices “that we have gotten used to,” such as wearing masks, said the governor according to the channel CBS.
It is important that everyone maintains social distance.
That is why hotel rooms have also been provided in some locations.
In addition, coronavirus testing is to be performed in emergency lodging.
Damage was initially only reported from the coastal city of Port Mansfield.
Storm warning retracted again
With wind speeds of up to 150 km/h, “Hanna” made landfall on Padre Island right in front of the Texan coast, according to authorities.
The tropical storm was upgraded to the lowest level hurricane just before this.
For the coastal section from Port Mansfield to Sargent, a storm surge warning was initially issued and then later retracted.
Authorities expected the storm to weaken as “Hanna” moves further inland and head towards northeastern Mexico.
“Douglas” moves towards Hawaii
In the Pacific, hurricane “Douglas” was on the move Saturday night at wind speeds of around 150 km/h heading towards Hawaii.
The Hurricane Center, however, expected the hurricane to weaken further.
Models predict it should be near to the largest Hawaiian island on Sunday (local time) - but then it will be a storm, just before the hurricane threshold.
NOAA expected a more active hurricane season over the Atlantic than average this year, according to a forecast from May.
Up to ten hurricanes are expected from June to the end of November, six of which could become very strong, authorities stated.
On average, there are six hurricanes over the Atlantic per year, while three of them develop into severe storms.
Given the available climate data and the higher water temperature in the Atlantic and Caribbean, the probability of a normal season is only 30 percent and the probability of a below-average season is just 10 percent, information says.
US president Donald Trump wrote on Twitter that his administration was observing the storms closely and he is in contact with the affected states.
Four goals denied: Video Assistant Referee “penalizes” Sassuolo
Sassuolo’s Filip Djuricic was denied two goals
Naples - Four goals scored, four goals denied: Sassuolo Calcio had a dark evening with 0:2 (0:1) at the SSC Naples in the Italian soccer league Serie A - and was really mad at the VAR.
