The path to the final in Lisbon “is not that easy,” emphasized the head coach, who can rely on the services of his new assistant-in-training Miroslav Klose, starting on Tuesday.
The world championship record goal scorer and Flick know what matters when going from 0-100 from preparing for so many tournaments.
With his current team, the work is “a delight,” praises Flick.
The “focus on winning” is an impressive characteristic of his team.
They excitedly competed with nine-man teams on Sunday.
All of the performers were there, including Thiago, who wants to leave, and defender David Alaba, who is not guaranteed to stay beyond the Champions League season.
Formula 1 needs a special rule to crown its world champion
Since the required number of continents cannot be driven on, the FIA needs to improvise to award the world champion title.
All American races have been cancelled.
The race calendar is becoming more concrete
The race calendar for the current Formula 1 season continues to take shape.
Three more race tracks were added this week to the ten confirmed Grand Prix so far.
There will be races on the Nürburgring in Germany and in Portimão in Portugal in October.
On November 1, Lewis Hamilton and company will battle it out for world championship points on the traditional Italian route in Imola.
The 2020 race calendar includes 13 circuits as it stands.
“We are looking forward making further progress in setting our plans for the 2020 season,” said Formula 1 boss Chase Carey.
In total, 15 to 18 races should be completed in the elite class of motor sports in this unusual season.
Then Formula 1 will end its season in Asia.
The final race calendar should be set and published in the coming weeks.
Of the races in Bahrain and Abu Dhabi in December that have already been homed in on, media reports state that there could also be races in Vietnam and Malaysia at the end of November.
Rules require races on three continents
The Formula 1 rules require at least one race on three continents to win the world championship.
Even if, as currently planned, races can only be held on two continents, there needs to be a world champion.
The FIA wants to use a special rule to award the title, invoking “exceptional circumstances” due to the coronavirus pandemic.
The traditional start of the season in Australia in March had to be cancelled at short notice due to the looming coronavirus crisis.
It won’t be possible to return to the continent this year.
In addition, Formula 1 won’t be invited to America this year.
Cancellation met with criticism in Brazil
The races in Canada, the US, Mexico and Brazil will not take place due to the fraught coronavirus situation.
“We are looking forward to being with you again next season,” says Carey.
The cancellation of the American races was met with criticism above all in Brazil: “For us, the cancellation is not surprising, but we cannot accept the reasons for this,” said Tamas Rohonyi, promoter of the Grand Prix in São Paulo.
The infection rates in the São Paulo region are much lower than in other regions in Brazil.
Some teams’ concerns of not wanting to drive in Brazil would also not justify a cancellation.
They are ready for the required safety measures.
Greta Thunberg: Mad look at Donald Trump goes around the world
Greta Thunberg spoke about her encounter with US president Donald Trump.
Greta Thunberg was a guest on Stephen Colbert’s late night show via video chat and revealed in the interview what she was thinking when she met Donald Trump.
Climate activist Greta Thunberg was a guest on the popular US late night show via video chat.
Among other things, she spoke about her struggle against powerful people in the world.
The teenager also talked about her famous “mad look” during her encounter with Donald Trump.
New York City - In the past two years, climate activist Greta Thunberg has made a name for herself with her tireless efforts for the “Fridays For Future” movement.
Now in a popular late night show, she spoke about her future plans as well as her encounter with the US president Donald Trump at the UN Climate Summit last year.
Late night moderator Stephen Colbert welcomed 17-year old Thunberg to his show on Tuesday and conducted a longer interview with the Swede.
Not only did she talk about her fight against climate change, but also her conflict with the powerful in the world.
“There are some things that surprised me,” she said.
“How far people go to distract from the climate crisis,” she stated.
She said she has experienced “everything from organized hate campaigns to threats, just because a group of kids take to the streets.”
She thinks heads of state and leading politicians who make fun of her on social media or even try to silence her are “funny,” because their reactions show that “they don’t have any other response.”
Things got particularly interesting at the end of the interview when Greta Thunberg was asked about a famous scene in which she threw a mean look at the US president Trump.
At the UN Climate Summit 2019 in New York, for which the activist sailed across the Atlantic, her expressive look was captured by the cameras and has since been viewed by countless people on the Internet.
A GIF was made of the short clip, which finally became one of the most used images for Trump opponents.
But what was the 17-year old thinking in this moment about the US president?
She only answered briefly and dryly to the question from Stephen Colbert, which she is asked often;: “To be honest, I don’t think you need an explanation.”
The experienced satirist Colbert certainly wasn’t expecting the response and briefly disappeared from view laughing.
Many at the climate conference will remember her for her “How dare you?” speech about the principles of climate protection.
Former Dortmund player Immobile scores hat trick for Lazio Rome
In the race for Europe’s Golden Boot, Ciro Immobile is now level with Bayern’s Robert Lewandowski.
Former Dortmund player Ciro Immobile still has a very good chance of being the top scorer in the Italian league.
The one-time BVB star scored three in Lazio’s 5:1 (1:1) victory over Hellas Verona, including two penalties in additional time in each half.
