In Italy, Cristiano Ronaldo follows with 30 goals so far, the Portuguese superstar having scored for the league leaders in the evening against Sampdoria Genoa.
Fleetwood Mac co-founder Peter Green dies
His life was like a roller coaster ride: after a swift ascent with Fleetwood Mac, things went sharply downhill and then slowly upwards again.
Now blues-rock guitarist Peter Green has died at the age of 73.
Genial guitarist, junkie, cult follower: The co-founder of band Fleetwood Mac, Peter Green, is dead.
He died peacefully in his sleep at the age of 73, reported family members on Saturday in an official announcement, with a further announcement to come in the next few days.
Leading musicians such as Peter Frampton recognized Green as one of the best blues and rock guitarists.
In an emotional reaction, Mick Fleetwood spoke of a “monumental loss” for all former and current members of Fleetwood Mac.
Drummer Fleetwood and guitarist Green founded the legendary group in London in 1967, and their dreamy instrumental hit “Albatross” has never been forgotten.
The musician’s ("The End Of The Game", "In The Skies") life resembled a roller coaster ride.
Green experienced a dramatic rise with Fleetwood Mac - but the group then enjoyed its greatest successes without him.
It is said that one dispute occurred because Green wanted to donate all of the band’s earnings to good causes.
He began to perform in flowing robes and with a large crucifix.
Psychological problems are also said to have played a part.
Green left the band three years after it was formed, in 1970.
A social decline followed.
The blues-rock guitarist suffered from drug abuse and schizophrenia, biographers reported.
For a long time Green received psychiatric treatment.
The musician vanished into thin air for a large part of the 1970s.
It is said that he sometimes lived on the streets, worked as a gardener in a cemetery, and spent some time on a kibbutz in Israel.
Green was born in 1946, the son of a Jewish working-class family in the London district of Bethnal Green.
Even when he was young he loved American blues musicians like B.B. King and Muddy Waters.
He learned his first guitar chords when he was eleven.
At the age of 15 the teenager began playing the guitar professionally and five years later he got the chance to take the stage as the lead guitarist for instrumental band Peter B’s Looners.
A little later he was hired by the Bluesbreakers as the replacement for his idol Eric Clapton.
In the summer of 1967, in the middle of the blues boom, Green founded Fleetwood Mac along with his Bluesbreaker co-members Mick Fleetwood and John McVie.
The song “Albatross”, composed by Green, brought the group their first number 1 hit in the winter of 1968/69, and catapulted them to the top of the British music scene.
But soon the rapid ascent showed its darker sides - Green was unable to cope with the media hype and his experiments with LSD grew increasingly extreme.
Later, in an interview, he commented on life between music and addiction, “The worst thing that has happened to me in my life is the drugs; the best was landing a number 1 hit”.
Towards the end of the decade, in 1979, Green surprisingly had a notable success with an album inspired by religious themes.
Meanwhile, without him, Fleetwood Mac were swimming on a wave of success with a new line-up.
Their album “Rumours”, released in 1977, sold over 40 million copies worldwide.
Despite various minor solo successes, Green did not achieve any major comeback until he started afresh with a group of his musician friends in 1996.
At the time, Britain’s “Daily Telegraph” spoke of a rock star that had come back down to earth.
Free of drugs, Green and the Peter Green Splinter Group released various albums before the band split up in 2004.
For music experts he was a blues legend even in his own lifetime - and with his gentle sound he was one of the most influential guitarists of recent decades.
